         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] accumulated (rebirth) is sorrow, too</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] because of their bad deeds (the bad)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (he who has excessively) bad morals</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (like) [his] enemy wishes [to have] (him) [SKT] (one does not become) an elder (just because)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] (he is called) “pseudo-old”</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (who has put aside [merit and evil], who leads the pure life) [SKT] (who goes) in dissociation</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] [if] (one is telling lies) without restraint</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels"><bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/><citedRange>187-189</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:chakravarti1930"/><citedRange>129-134</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:hahn2007"/><citedRange>45-46</citedRange></bibl>. See also <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-ioltoch505"/>.</note><note type="remarks">On <ref target="http://idp.bl.uk/database/oo_loader.a4d?pm=IOL%20Toch%20807" type="external">IDP</ref>, recto and verso are reversed.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Uv.11.8d <hi>duḥkhāś copacitā bhavāḥ</hi>. In the Tocharian translation, <hi>lä(k)l(e)</hi> 'sorrow' is singular, unlike Skt. <hi>duḥkhāś</hi>, which is plural.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Uv.11.9c <hi>pāpā hi karmabhiḥ pāpair</hi></note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">Uv.11.10a <hi>yo ’sāv atyantaduḥśīlaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#b1" type="lingcomment"><hi>sāñ</hi>: a variant of <hi>sān</hi>, nom.sg. ‘enemy’, in sandhi before the following <hi>ñäṣträ</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Uv.11.10d-11a <hi>yathainaṃ dviṣa-d icchati // 10 sthaviro na tāvatā bhavati</hi></note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment"><hi>10</hi>: something that might be the stroke of <hi>11</hi> is seen above, but we expect just <hi>10</hi> because pāda 11 follows.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Uv.11.11d <hi>mohajīrṇaḥ sa ucyate</hi></note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Uv.11.12b-c <hi>prahāya brahmacaryavān / viśreṇayitvā carati</hi></note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">Uv.11.13b <hi>hy avṛtas tv anṛtaṃ vadan</hi>; the hiatus-resolving <hi>hy</hi> is lacking in this version (this occurs frequently with these pādas divided in two, because there is no hiatus anyway, cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1974"/><citedRange>82</citedRange></bibl>, <bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1977a"/><citedRange>271</citedRange></bibl> and e.g. <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht101"/> a3 <hi>as(m)iṃ</hi> for <hi>hy asmiṃ</hi>).</note></p>
         </div>
